{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"The generated function signature matches the expected interface (parameter names, types, return type) specified in the description.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"Boundary proof: Unit->Integration because prompt construction, code extraction, and signature validator can disagree at module handoff (e.g., parser drops type hints). Integration->System because the generation step uses a real external LLM API call (network/request formatting/token limits) that mocks cannot reproduce exactly. System->Agentic because correctness depends on real model output quality and variability in signature adherence. Rejection gate: not Workflow because behavior text only requires signature correctness for generation output, not multiple agentic steps in sequence.","test_description":"Run real LLM generation for several interface-constrained prompts; compile/parse output and assert exact signature match (names, types, return). Repeat runs to catch nondeterministic signature drift.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.05,"Integration":0.12,"System":0.23,"Agentic":0.58,"Workflow":0.02}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"The generated implementation passes all provided test cases on the first or a subsequent attempt.","minimum_level":"Workflow","justification":"Boundary proof: Unit->Integration because orchestrator must hand off generated code to test runner and route pass/fail state back correctly. Integration->System because real LLM API invocation is external networked infrastructure. System->Agentic because pass/fail depends on actual model code-generation quality, not deterministic stubs. Agentic->Workflow because behavior text explicitly includes success on a subsequent attempt, requiring multiple agentic steps in sequence (generate/refine across attempts).","test_description":"Use a real model and real orchestration loop with a target function suite; assert service reports success when implementation passes either attempt 1 or a later allowed attempt, and verify attempt transitions are preserved.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.02,"Integration":0.08,"System":0.15,"Agentic":0.25,"Workflow":0.5}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"When tests fail, the refinement step includes the failure messages in the next LLM prompt so the model can learn from its mistakes.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Boundary proof: Unit->Integration because failure text must cross module boundaries (test runner result -> prompt builder -> LLM request payload); real bugs occur in this handoff (truncation/omission/wrong field). Integration brake: no required real OS/network/subprocess to validate inclusion itself; no dependence on model output quality; no multi-agentic-step requirement. Rejection gate: not System/Agentic because behavior text is about prompt content inclusion, which can be verified by inspecting constructed next prompt payload with deterministic doubles.","test_description":"Wire orchestrator + prompt builder + test-result adapter in-process; inject failing test output and assert next-attempt prompt contains exact failure messages (including multiline/stack traces) and correct association to the failed attempt.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.22,"Integration":0.68,"System":0.06,"Agentic":0.03,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"The service stops after 3 failed attempts and returns a structured error with all three attempts and their test results.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Boundary proof: Unit->Integration because retry controller, execution result store, and API response serializer must coordinate attempt count/state across modules; off-by-one and dropped-attempt bugs appear at these interfaces. Integration brake: no required real OS/network/subprocess for stop-at-3 logic; no required AI output-quality